The paper deals with the Johnson-Lindenstrauss lemma, which is a fundamental result in high dimensional geometry and has applications in various areas of computer science such as data structures, information theory, computational geometry, numerical analysis, and machine learning. Therefore, the paper could potentially belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories. 

cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is the most likely category as the paper deals with the design and analysis of algorithms in high dimensional geometry. 

cs.IT (Information Theory) is also a likely category as the paper discusses the use of randomness in linear embeddings, which is a common topic in information theory. 

cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is another likely category as the Johnson-Lindenstrauss lemma is a fundamental result in computational geometry. 

cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) is a possible category as the paper deals with the distortion of linear embeddings, which is a topic in numerical analysis. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a possible category as the Johnson-Lindenstrauss lemma has applications in machine learning, particularly in dimensionality reduction.
